cally alter the shape and tempo of everyday life in Berlin. The resulting consciousness of accelerated social change and the shocks and afflictions that accompanied it found their consummate expression in the discourse about nervousness. Wonderfully researched and clearly written, this book offers a wealth of new insights into the nature of the modern metropolis, the psychological aftermath of World War I, and the operations of the German welfare state. Killen also explores cultural attitudes toward electricity, the evolution of psychiatric thought and practice, and the status of women workers in Germany's rapidly industrializing economy. Ultimately, he argues that the backlash against the welfare state that occurred during the late Weimar Republic brought about the final decoupling of modernity and nervous illness.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aElectrificationxHistoryxGermanyxBerlin. 0aElectrificationzGermanyzBerlinxHistory. 0aElectrotherapeuticsxHistoryxGermanyxBerlin. 0aElectrotherapeuticszGermanyzBerlinxHistory. 0aIndustrializationxPsychological aspectsxGermanyxBerlin. 0aIndustrializationzGermanyzBerlinxPsychological aspects. 0aMental fatiguexSocial aspectsxHistoryxGermanyxBerlin. 0aMental fatiguexSocial aspectszGermanyzBerlinxHistory. 0aNeurastheniaxSocial aspectsxHistoryxGermanyxBerlin. 0aNeurastheniaxSocial aspectszGermanyzBerlinxHistory. 0aPsychiatryxHistoryxGermanyxBerlin. 0aPsychiatryzGermanyzBerlinxHistory. 0aRailroadsxEmployeesxMental healthxGermanyxBerlin. 0aRailroadsxEmployeesxMental healthzGermanyzBerlin. 0aSocial changexPsychological aspectsxGermanyxBerlin. 0aSocial changezGermanyzBerlinxPsychological aspects. 0aSoldiersxMental healthxGermanyxBerlin. 0aSoldiersxMental healthzGermanyzBerlin. 0aTelephone opera